{{Infobox person |name=Christopher Hinton |birth_date={{birth year and age|1952}} |birth_place=[[Galt, Ontario]], Canada |death_date= |death_place= |occupation=Animator, film director, professor }}
'''Christopher Hinton''' (b. 1952 Galt, Ontario) is a Canadian film animator, film director and professor, living in [[Victoria, British Columbia]], Canada. Hinton's films have won international awards and been twice nominated for an [[Academy Award for Best Animated Short Film]]: in 1991 for the [[National Film Board of Canada]] (NFB) animated short film ''[[Blackfly (film)|Blackfly]]'' and in 2003 for his independently made short ''Nibbles''. Hinton won a [[Genie Award for Best Animated Short|Genie Award]] for his 2004 short film ''[[cNote (film)|cNote]]''.<ref name="black">{{cite news|last=Black|first=Barbara|title=Abstract art-and-music pas de deux wins a Genie|url=http://cjournal.concordia.ca/journalarchives/2005-06/mar_23/006572.shtml|accessdate=22 October 2010|newspaper=Concordia Journal|date=23 March 2006|volume=1 |number=10}}</ref> He began freelancing for the NFB in Winnipeg in the 1970s. He has written and directed over a dozen films for the National Film Board and CBC Sesame Street. Recent films, ''Flux'' (NFB,2003), ''cNote'' (NFB, 2005), ''Chroma Concerto'' (2007), and ''Compression'' (2008), explore the boundaries of narrative and abstraction and the integration of contemporary media into the moving image. He was a full-time professor in the Animation Program at [[Concordia University (Quebec)|Concordia University]].<ref name="lenburg">{{cite book|last=Lenburg|first=Jeff|title=Who's Who in Animated Cartoons: An International Guide to Film and Television's Award-Winning and Legendary Animators |publisher=Applause Books|isbn=1-55783-671-X|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FVShFCjVzvIC&pg=PA141&dq=blackfly+hinton&hl=en&ei=b6jBTLyhOo-t8AbwwtjlBg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=8&ved=0CFAQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&q=blackfly%20hinton&f=false|page=141|date=June 1, 2006}}</ref>
